prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: B7 continuum: Borasisi
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note:
This project aims to measure Borosisi's continuum at band 7 to constrain its diameter, hence density (mass measurements are known, Grundy et al. 2011)
The target is a moving object. Therefore, the most recent ephemeris at the time of the observation should be used for the field setup (coordinates, proper motion).

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: Correlator setup: Our objective is to detect the continuum emission. Therefore, we only require the low-resolution/TDM correlator setup, with a spectral resolution of 31.25 MHz and the largest bandwidth available: 2 GHz in the 4 basebands in dual polarization, and any spatial resolution (point source).
Our target is a point source. It can therefore be observed in any array configuration.

Time constraints: TNOs are moving objects. The target needs to be observed when high in the sky (elevation >30 deg). The most recent ephemeris at the time of the observation should be used for the field setup (coordinates, proper motion).
SNR: Borasisi is a very faint object based on the Spitzer-Herschel results. Its expected thermal flux at 350 Ghz ranges from 23 to 122 micronJy. Targeting a 20 micronJy rms (2 hours on source, will ensure a 1-7 sigma detection. Note that the current upper limit on the albedo is 67%, which is highly unlikely for a Solar System small body. We therefore expect a detection at SNR>3. If the detection is very poor, this will confirm Borasisi is indeed a very small object with a very strong albedo, and therefore an outlier of the global size/density picture.
The expected fluxes in band 7 (and accompanying rms) were calculated using a model developed by Groussin et al. [Groussin et al. 2011] and exposure times using the ALMA Integration Time Calculator.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: Compared to the overall population of small Trans-Neptunian Objects (TNOs), the possible high density of Borasisi makes it a possible interloper in the Kuiper Belt. Of great interest, the presence of interlopers has been predicted by the most recent Solar System formation models which invoke an important radial mixing of planetesimals due to the early migration of Jupiter. The existence of these objects would further provide a solution for explaining the large and dense objects, which could then form by coagulation of smaller but comparable in density objects. Hence, it is key to establish whether such small, dense objects exist in the Kuiper Belt. The current uncertainty on Borasisi's density measurement is however too large to unambiguously assess a different composition and origin for this TNO. We will perform a 2h continuum flux observation of Borasisi at Band 7, which will allow us to refine the estimate of its equivalent diameter, hence density. Currently, only ALMA has the sensitivity to measure the thermal emission of this target.
